\end_inset

In Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS), a brief (0.2
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

ms) and powerful (0.2~4.0
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

T) magnetic pulse is generated by the coil.
 The coil is excited by the pulsing electric current, that reaches its maximal
 intensity within 0.1~0.2
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

ms and then decreases to zero during next 0.5~1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

ms.
 Rapid ramping of the magnetic flux leads to formation of an eddy currents
 in the conductive sections of the tissue.
 Eddy currents flow in closed loops in planes perpendicular to the magnetic
 field.
 
\end_layout

