\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:TES"

\end_inset

Transcranial electric stimulation (tES)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While in TMS the electric current is induced in the conductive parts of
 the tissue using external and rapidly changing magnetic field, in tES a
 weak electric current (0.1~2.0 mA) is applied on scalp using electrodes and
 flows through the tissue.
 The current flow in not homogenous and has variability among the affected
 tissue.
 The most of the current is conducted by surface layers (skin) and only
 small portion penetrates cortex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on time course of the electric current, tES can be divided to 
\emph on
transcranial direct current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tDCS
\emph default
), 
\emph on
transcranial alternating current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tACS
\emph default
), 
\emph on
transcranial random noise stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tRNS
\emph default
) and 
\emph on
transcranial pulsed current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tPCS
\emph default
) (for reviews see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Paulus2011a,Guleyupoglu2013a"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Electrode area and placement are important attributes.
 Area of the electrode must be chosen in accordance to the density and time
 course of the current to avoid pathological changes in the tissue.
 In order to decrease current spatial variability, multiple electrodes of
 same polarity can be placed in circular shape around one electrode of other
 polarity.
 This has been used to enhance focality of tDCS and it is denoted as 
\emph on
high-definition tDCS
\emph default
 (
\emph on
HD-tDCS
\emph default
) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Caparelli-Daquer2012a"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
tDCS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In tDCS a direct current with intensity of 0.4~2
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

mA is applied on scalp via electrode pads for 5~30
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

minutes.
 Current causes most of the changes right under the electrodes: under cathode
 it decreases excitability of cortical neurons and under the anode the effect
 is opposite.
 By changing the area of the electrodes a current density can be changed
 and thus the effect of the stimulation.
 The effects last for few hours after the stimulation ends as in TMS.
 In clinical use, tDCS is considered as a noninvasive stimulation that is
 affordable and easy to use compare to other neuromodulatory techniques.
 TDCS is a promising method for the treatment of chronic pain 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "OConnell2014"

\end_inset

, as well as for patients with neuropsychiatric diseases and other neurological
 disorders 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kuo2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Novel approaches (tACS, tPCS, tRNS)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
About novel approaches of transcranial electric stimulation is not known
 too much.
 In 
\emph on
transcranial alternating current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tACS
\emph default
) an oscillatory electric current is delivered to the cortical tissue with
 oscillation frequency between 0.1~5000
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Hz.
 It is thought that the tACS signal interacts with ongoing cortical oscillations
 and induce changes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Antal2013"

\end_inset

.
 Another method, 
\emph on
transcranial pulse current stimulation
\emph default
 (
\emph on
tPCS
\emph default
), is a variation of tACS where the harmonic current is exchanged for the
 rectangular electric signal.
 Though the spectra in tPCS is wider, the dominant frequency is still the
 baseline frequency of the pulses.
 Recently, interest has emerged in new stimulation method, transcranial
 random noise stimulation (tRNS) in which a random noise signal is applied
 with the frequency spectrum normaly distributed over given frequency range.
 tRNS is usually divided to low- (0.1~100
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Hz) and high-frequency tRNS (100~640
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Hz) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Terney2008"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

