\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It has been presented that numerical electromagnetic (EM) simulations (solving
 Maxwell’s equations) are powerful tools for estimation of distribution
 of magnetic and electric field induced by transcranial stimulation (TS)
 inside the human head.
 From distribution of magnetic and electric field electrical current density
 distribution can be computed.
 Most numerical simulations used for modeling of TS are based on finite
 element method (FEM).
 In literature some simplifications of realistic model of human head were
 used.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Wagner2004"

\end_inset

 FEM is used to evaluate the induced electric current density in simplified
 model, head was approximated by a sphere, exposed by a time varying magnetic
 field.
 A more accurate prediction of the field distribution can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Golestanirad2010,Datta2009,Bikson2012,Bikson2012a"

\end_inset

, where different 3-D patient specific numerical head phantoms (anatomically
 accurate numerical head models) have been developed.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Golestanirad2010"

\end_inset

 the phantoms were created using head imaging data of individual patients.
 The simulations were performed with relatively course mesh and difference
 between electrical properties of cerebrospinal fluid and brain white/gray
 matter was neglected.
 The side effect of TS therapy in form of temperature increase was published
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "March2014"

\end_inset

.
 Improvements in coil performance would have a signiﬁcant impact in extending
 the usefulness of TS in clinical applications 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tsuyama2009"

\end_inset

.
 New design and optimization of coil for the treatment optimization in sense
 of ability to stimulate the brain at depth and with high spatial locality,
 was described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tsuyama2009"

\end_inset

.
 Also the electrode placement has been studied and 4x1 ring electrode assembly
 has been proposed to increase focality of the stimulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Datta2009,Caparelli-Daquer2012a,Edwards2013"

\end_inset

.
